** What Makes a Hero and the True Measure of the Human Spirit: Walter Lipp=
mann=E2=80=99s Stunning Tribute to Amelia Earhart (https://www.brainpickin=
gs.org/2016/09/08/walter-lippmann-amelia-earhart/?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_e=
id=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/B0006AYKOQ/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Dba2=
45eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

What is it that gives the human spirit wings to soar above the trenches of=
 tradition=2C above the flatlands of convention=2C above even the highest=
 peaks of the probable into ever-greater altitudes of possibility?

That=E2=80=99s what the great journalist and essayist Walter Lippmann (Sep=
tember 23=2C 1889=E2=80=93December 14=2C 1974) explores in a beautiful pie=
ce published in his New York Herald Tribune column=2C Today and Tomorrow=
=2C on July 8=2C 1937 =E2=80=94 six days after Amelia Earhart (https://www=
=2Ebrainpickings.org/tag/amelia-earhart/?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQ=
ID]) disappeared over the Pacific Ocean=2C leaving behind a decades-long c=
omet tail of courage that has since inspired generations.

Lippmann=E2=80=99s requiem=2C eventually included in The Essential Lippman=
n: A Political Philosophy for Liberal Democracy (http://www.amazon.com/exe=
c/obidos/ASIN/B0006AYKOQ/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID=
]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.org/title/essential-lippmann-a-pol=
itical-philosophy-for-liberal-democracy/oclc/193769&referer=3Dbrief_result=
s?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) )=2C stands as a counterpart=2C=
 perhaps even a precondition=2C to Alexander Flexner=E2=80=99s wonderful d=
efense of =E2=80=9Cthe usefulness of useless knowledge.=E2=80=9D (https://=
www.brainpickings.org/2012/07/27/the-usefulness-of-useless-knowledge/?mc_c=
id=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) What Lippmann crafts is a beautiful ca=
se for the usefulness of useless curiosity and courage=2C through the siev=
e of which all truly useful knowledge and human achievement must pass.

Walter Lippmann

Half a century before Joseph Campbell conceived of his eleven stages of th=
e hero=E2=80=99s journey (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/04/28/what-ma=
kes-a-hero-joseph-campbell-monomyth/?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID=
]) and before pioneering biochemist lamented how how the excessive pragmat=
ization of science is sapping its courage and poetic curiosity (https://ww=
w.brainpickings.org/2016/06/13/erwin-chargaff-heraclitean-fire-science/?mc=
_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Lippmann considers the heroism o=
f unbridled curiosity:

I cannot quite remember whether Miss Earhart undertook her flight with som=
e practical purpose in mind=2C say=2C to demonstrate something or other ab=
out aviation which will make it a little easier for commercial passengers=
 to move more quickly around the world. There are those who seem to think=
 that an enterprise like hers must have some such justification=2C that wi=
thout it there was no good reason for taking such grave risks.

But in truth Miss Earhart needs no such justification. The world is a bett=
er place to live in because it contains human beings who will give up ease=
 and security and stake their own lives in order to do what they themselve=
s think worth doing. They help to offset the much larger numbers who are r=
eady to sacrifice the ease and the security and the very lives of others i=
n order to do what they want done.

Writing on the cusp of World War II=2C Lippmann admonishes against mistaki=
ng force for fortitude and argues that =E2=80=9Csynthetic heroes=E2=80=9D=
 and =E2=80=9Cmen in bulletproof vests surrounded by squads of armed guard=
s=E2=80=9D are the measure not of humanity=E2=80=99s strength but of our w=
eakness. Heroes like Amelia Earhart offer a different=2C truer conception=
 of courage. He writes:

It is somehow reassuring to think that there are also men and women who ta=
ke the risks themselves=2C who pit themselves not against their fellow bei=
ngs but against the immensity and the violence of the natural world=2C who=
 are brave without cruelty to others and impassioned with an idea that dig=
nifies all who contemplate it.

Amelia Earhart

Lippmann ends with a sentiment that transcends Earhart=E2=80=99s particula=
r feat and extends to triumphs of the human spirit as diverse as the inven=
tion of the world=E2=80=99s first computer (https://www.brainpickings.org/=
2015/06/15/the-thrilling-adventures-of-lovelace-and-babbage-sydney-padua/?=
mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C the first polar expeditions (h=
ttps://www.brainpickings.org/2014/02/26/shackletons-journey-william-grill-=
nobrow/?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and the century-long q=
uest to hear the sound of spacetime (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/04=
/25/black-hole-blues-janna-levin-joseph-weber/?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) :

The best things of mankind are as useless as Amelia Earhart=E2=80=99s adve=
nture. They are the things that are undertaken not for some definite=2C me=
asurable result=2C but because someone=2C not counting the costs or calcul=
ating the consequences=2C is moved by curiosity=2C the love of excellence=
=2C a point of honor=2C the compulsion to invent or to make or to understa=
nd. In such persons mankind overcomes the inertia which would keep it eart=
hbound forever in its habitual ways. They have in them the free and useles=
s energy with which alone men surpass themselves.

Such energy cannot be planned and managed and made purposeful=2C or weight=
ed by the standards of utility or judged by its social consequences. It is=
 wild and it is free. But all the heroes=2C the saints=2C the seers=2C the=
 explorers and the creators partake of it. They do not know what they disc=
over. They do not know where their impulse is taking them. They can give n=
o account in advance of where they are going or explain completely where t=
hey have been. They have been possessed for a time with an extraordinary p=
assion which is unintelligible in ordinary terms.

No preconceived theory fits them. No material purpose actuates them. They=
 do the useless=2C brave=2C noble=2C the divinely foolish and the very wis=
est things that are done by man. And what they prove to themselves and to=
 others is that man is no mere creature of his habits=2C no mere automaton=
 in his routine=2C no mere cog in the collective machine=2C but that in th=
e dust of which he is made there is also fire=2C lighted now and then by g=
reat winds from the sky.

All of Lippmann=E2=80=99s cultural observations gathered in The Essential=
 Lippmann (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/B0006AYKOQ/braipick-20?m=
c_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) emanate these transcendent overtone=
s of lyrical and lucid idealism. Complement this particular portion with t=
his modern manifesto for nurturing tomorrow=E2=80=99s Amelias (https://www=
=2Ebrainpickings.org/2016/03/01/gutsy-girl-caroline-paul/?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f=
0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and Earhart herself on marriage (https://www.brainpi=
ckings.org/2012/12/11/amelia-earhart-on-marriage/?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_e=
id=3D[UNIQID]) =2C motivation and human nature (https://www.brainpickings=
=2Eorg/2013/07/24/amelia-earhart-letters-2/?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[U=
NIQID]) =2C and sticking up for yourself (https://www.brainpickings.org/20=
15/07/24/amelia-earhart-lettrs-sister/?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQ=
ID]) .

For a contemporary embodiment of Lippmann=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cuseless=2C br=
ave=2C noble=E2=80=A6 divinely foolish=E2=80=A6 very wisest=E2=80=9D pursu=
its=2C devour the exhilarating story of LIGO and the quest to detect gravi=
tational waves (http://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/24/books/review/maria-popov=
a-reviews-janna-levins-black-hole-blues.html?_r=3D1&mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc=
_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .

Thanks=2C Dawn (http://www.dawnlandes.com/?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[=
UNIQID])


