** The Terror of Kindness: Ta-Nehisi Coates on Overriding Our Cultural Con=
ditioning and Living Beyond Fear (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/07=
/ta-nehisi-coates-kindness-fear/?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0812993543/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Dba2=
45eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ve got to be as clear-headed about human beings as pos=
sible=2C because we are still each other=E2=80=99s only hope=2C=E2=80=9D J=
ames Baldwin said to Margaret Mead in their forgotten=2C acutely timely co=
nversation about race=2C forgiveness=2C and the crucial difference between=
 guilt and responsibility (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/03/19/a-rap-=
on-race-margaret-mead-and-james-baldwin/?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UN=
IQID]) . And yet when trauma=2C injustice=2C and cultural conditioning sme=
ar our vision with blood and tears=2C we begin to lose sight of this essen=
tial=2C life-affirming truth.

That=E2=80=99s what Ta-Nehisi Coates=2C a Baldwin-plus of our time=2C addr=
esses in a beautiful passage from the altogether stirring Between the Worl=
d and Me (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0812993543/braipick-20?mc=
_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worldcat=
=2Eorg/title/between-the-world-and-me/oclc/912045191&referer=3Dbrief_results=
?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ).

Ta-Nehisi Coates (Photograph: Gabriella Demczuk (http://www.gabriellademcz=
uk.com/?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) for The New York Times)

Coates reflects on the transformative experience of his first visit to Par=
is =E2=80=94 a perspective-reorienting pilgrimage he made from West Baltim=
ore=2C by way of Harlem=2C as soon as he received his first adult passport=
:

It occurred to me that I really was in someone else=E2=80=99s country and=
 yet=2C in some necessary way=2C I was outside of their country. In Americ=
a I was part of an equation =E2=80=94 even if it wasn=E2=80=99t a part I r=
elished. I was the one the police stopped on Twenty-third Street in the mi=
ddle of a workday. I was the one driven to The Mecca. I was not just a fat=
her but the father of a black boy. I was not just a spouse but the husband=
 of a black woman=2C a freighted symbol of black love. But sitting in that=
 garden=2C for the first time I was an alien=2C I was a sailor =E2=80=94 l=
andless and disconnected. And I was sorry that I had never felt this parti=
cular loneliness before =E2=80=94 that I had never felt myself so far outs=
ide of someone else=E2=80=99s dream.

Loneliness (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/11/the-lonely-city-olivi=
a-laing/?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 particularly th=
e loneliness familiar to those of us who are immigrants or alien in any ot=
her way=2C the kind that comes from being in a culture but not of it (http=
s://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/05/alfred-kazin-walker-in-the-city-love/=
?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 is a paradoxical emotio=
n=2C stretched between longing and fear: we long for inclusion=2C acceptan=
ce=2C and equal belonging=2C but fear we=E2=80=99d be hurt=2C rejected=2C=
 or violated in the vulnerable-making act of making our longing manifest.=
 The fear takes over =E2=80=94 especially if it carries the momentum of pr=
evious violations=2C be they personal or inherited =E2=80=94 and erects a=
 protective wall that only further separates us from the very thing we lon=
g for.

With an eye to that divisive fear=2C Coates addresses his young son:

We came back to Paris that summer=2C because your mother loved the city an=
d because I loved the language=2C but above all because of you.

I wanted you to have your own life=2C apart from fear =E2=80=94 even apart=
 from me. I am wounded. I am marked by old codes=2C which shielded me in o=
ne world and then chained me in the next. I think of your grandmother call=
ing me and noting how you were growing tall and would one day try to =E2=
=80=9Ctest me.=E2=80=9D And I said to her that I would regard that day=2C=
 should it come=2C as the total failure of fatherhood because if all I had=
 over you were my hands=2C then I really had nothing at all. But=2C forgiv=
e me=2C son=2C I knew what she meant and when you were younger I thought t=
he same. And I am now ashamed of the thought=2C ashamed of my fear=2C of t=
he generational chains I tried to clasp onto your wrists. We are entering=
 our last years together=2C and I wish I had been softer with you. Your mo=
ther had to teach me how to love you =E2=80=94 how to kiss you and tell yo=
u I love you every night. Even now it does not feel a wholly natural act s=
o much as it feels like ritual. And that is because I am wounded. That is=
 because I
am tied to old ways=2C which I learned in a hard house. It was a loving ho=
use even as it was besieged by its country=2C but it was hard. Even in Par=
is=2C I could not shake the old ways=2C the instinct to watch my back at e=
very pass=2C and always be ready to go.

A few weeks into our stay=2C I made a friend who wanted to improve his Eng=
lish as much as I wanted to improve my French. We met one day out in the c=
rowd in front of Notre Dame. We walked to the Latin Quarter. We walked to=
 a wine shop. Outside the wine shop there was seating. We sat and drank a=
 bottle of red. We were served heaping piles of meats=2C bread=2C and chee=
se. Was this dinner? Did people do this? I had not even known how to imagi=
ne it. And more=2C was this all some elaborate ritual to get an angle on m=
e? My friend paid. I thanked him. But when we left I made sure he walked o=
ut first. He wanted to show me one of those old buildings that seem to be=
 around every corner in that city. And the entire time he was leading me=
=2C I was sure he was going to make a quick turn into an alley=2C where so=
me dudes would be waiting to strip me of =E2=80=A6 what=2C exactly? But my=
 new friend simply showed me the building=2C shook my hand=2C gave a fine=
 bonne soir=C3=A9e=2C and walked off into the wide open night.
And watching him walk away=2C I felt that I had missed part of the experie=
nce because of my eyes=2C because my eyes were made in Baltimore=2C becaus=
e my eyes were blindfolded by fear. What I wanted was to put as much dista=
nce between you and that blinding fear as possible.

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0812993543/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Dba2=
45eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Complement this particular fragment of the thoroughly terrific Between the=
 World and Me (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0812993543/braipick-=
20?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) with psychoanalyst Adam Phillip=
s and historian Barbara Taylor on how kindness became our forbidden pleasu=
re (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/07/13/on-kindness-adam-phillips-bar=
