Stefanie Posavec

Here is my foreword essay=2C as it appears in the book:

=E2=80=9CMy experience is what I agree to attend to=2C=E2=80=9D William Ja=
mes wrote (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/03/25/william-james-attentio=
n/?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) at the dawn of modern psycholog=
y. And yet however perennial this insight may be=2C it is only a partial t=
ruth. Our experience is shaped as much by what we agree to take in as it i=
s by what we refuse =E2=80=94 what we choose to leave out =E2=80=94 and bo=
th are only partly conscious choices. Our attention filters in a fraction=
 of what goes on around us at any given moment and filters out=2C thanks t=
o millions of years of evolution=2C the vast majority of the shimmering si=
multaneity with which the life of sensation and perception unfolds. This h=
ighly subjective=2C selective=2C imperfect filtration of reality guarantee=
s that however many parallels two human beings may have between their live=
s=2C however much common ground=2C the paths by which they navigate their=
 respective landscapes of experience will be profoundly divergent.

In their yearlong visual correspondence project=2C Giorgia Lupi=2C an Ital=
ian woman living in New York=2C and Stefanie Posavec=2C an American woman=
 living in London=2C capture the inherent poetry of that subjective select=
ivity. Each week=2C they jointly select one aspect of daily life =E2=80=94=
 from sleep to spending habits to mirror use =E2=80=94 and depict their re=
spective experience of it in a hand-drawn visualization on the back of a p=
ostcard=2C then mail it to the other. Out of these simple diurnal observat=
ions emerges the complexity of the human experience =E2=80=94 nonlinear=2C=
 contradictory=2C and always filtered through the discriminating yet imper=
fect lens of attention.

The creative constraint of the unifying themes only amplifies the variousn=
ess of possibility within each parameter. Despite the substantial similari=
ties between the two women =E2=80=94 both are information designers known=
 for working by hand=2C both are only children=2C both have left their res=
pective homeland to move across the Atlantic in pursuit of creative fulfil=
lment=2C and they are the exact same age =E2=80=94 their attentional orien=
tation toward each week=E2=80=99s chosen subject is completely different=
=2C both in substance and in style. They deliberately use different visual=
 metaphors and information design techniques for each week=E2=80=99s theme=
=2C producing is an immensely pleasurable duet of sensibilities =E2=80=94=
 side by side=2C Posavec=E2=80=99s signature spatial poetics and Lupi=E2=
=80=99s mastery of shape and color elevate one another to a higher plane o=
f meaning and delight.

A twenty-first-century testament to Virginia Woolf=E2=80=99s celebration o=
f letter-writing as =E2=80=9Cthe humane art=2C=E2=80=9D (https://www.brain=
pickings.org/2014/11/20/the-humane-art-virginia-woolf/?mc_cid=3Dba245eb6f0=
&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) the project radiates a lovely countercultural charm.=
 Ours is the golden age of Big Data=2C where human lives are aggregated in=
to massive data sets in the hope that analysis of the aggregate would yiel=
d valid insight into the individual =E2=80=94 an approach no more effectiv=
e than taking an exquisite poem in English=2C running it through Google Tr=
anslate to render into Japanese=2C and then Google-translating it back int=
o English; the result may have the vague contours of the original poem=E2=
=80=99s meaning=2C but none of its subtle magic and vibrant granular beaut=
y.

Lupi and Posavec reclaim that poetic granularity of the individual from th=
e homogenizing aggregate-grip of Big Data. What emerges is a case for the=
 beauty of small data and its deliberate interpretation=2C analog visualiz=
ation=2C and slow transmission =E2=80=94 a celebration of the infinitesima=
l=2C incomplete=2C imperfect=2C yet marvelously human details through whic=
h we wrest meaning out of the incomprehensible vastness of all possible ex=
perience that is life.

