in-end: 0px;"><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adj=
ust: 100%;color: #808080;font-family: Arial=2C Sans-serif;font-size: 14px;=
line-height: 170%;text-align: left;"><img src=3D"https://gallery.mailchimp=
=2Ecom/13eb080d8a315477042e0d5b1/images/2e292385-dc1c-4cfe-b95e-845f6f98c2ec=
=2Epng" align=3D"left" style=3D"-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;border: 0;he=
ight: auto;line-height: 100%;outline: none;text-decoration: none;padding:=
 5px 30px 10px 0px;display: inline;width: 50px!important;">=E2=80=9CMy exp=
erience is what I agree to attend to=2C=E2=80=9D William James <a href=3D"=
http://brainpickings.us2.list-manage1.com/track/click?u=3D13eb080d8a315477=
042e0d5b1&id=3Df4cab1723b&e=3Da5eb5cdf67" style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adju=
st: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #C33737;text-decoration: underl=
ine;">wrote</a> at the dawn of modern psychology. And yet however perennia=
l this insight may be=2C it is only a partial truth. Our experience is sha=
ped as much by what we agree to take in as it is by what we refuse =E2=80=
=94 what we choose to leave out =E2=80=94 and both are only partly conscio=
us choices. Our attention filters in a fraction of what goes on around us=
 at any given moment and filters out=2C thanks to millions of years of evo=
lution=2C the vast majority of the shimmering simultaneity with which the=
 life of sensation and perception unfolds. This highly subjective=2C selec=
tive=2C imperfect filtration of reality guarantees that however many paral=
lels two human beings may have between their lives=2C however much common=
 ground=2C the paths by which they navigate their respective landscapes of=
 experience will be profoundly divergent. </p><p style=3D"-webkit-text-siz=
e-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #808080;font-family: Aria=
l=2C Sans-serif;font-size: 14px;line-height: 170%;text-align: left;">In th=
eir yearlong visual correspondence project=2C Giorgia Lupi=2C an Italian w=
oman living in New York=2C and Stefanie Posavec=2C an American woman livin=
g in London=2C capture the inherent poetry of that subjective selectivity.=
 Each week=2C they jointly select one aspect of daily life =E2=80=94 from=
 sleep to spending habits to mirror use =E2=80=94 and depict their respect=
ive experience of it in a hand-drawn visualization on the back of a postca=
rd=2C then mail it to the other. Out of these simple diurnal observations=
 emerges the complexity of the human experience =E2=80=94 nonlinear=2C con=
tradictory=2C and always filtered through the discriminating yet imperfect=
 lens of attention.</p><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text=
-size-adjust: 100%;color: #808080;font-family: Arial=2C Sans-serif;font-si=
ze: 14px;line-height: 170%;text-align: left;">The creative constraint of t=
he unifying themes only amplifies the variousness of possibility within ea=
ch parameter. Despite the substantial similarities between the two women=
 =E2=80=94 both are information designers known for working by hand=2C bot=
h are only children=2C both have left their respective homeland to move ac=
ross the Atlantic in pursuit of creative fulfillment=2C and they are the e=
xact same age =E2=80=94 their attentional orientation toward each week=E2=
=80=99s chosen subject is completely different=2C both in substance and in=
 style. They deliberately use different visual metaphors and information d=
esign techniques for each week=E2=80=99s theme=2C producing is an immensel=
y pleasurable duet of sensibilities =E2=80=94 side by side=2C Posavec=E2=
=80=99s signature spatial poetics and Lupi=E2=80=99s mastery of shape and=
 color elevate one another to a higher plane of meaning and delight. </p><=
p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color=
: #808080;font-family: Arial=2C Sans-serif;font-size: 14px;line-height: 17=
0%;text-align: left;">A twenty-first-century testament to Virginia Woolf=
=E2=80=99s celebration of letter-writing as <a href=3D"http://brainpicking=
s.us2.list-manage.com/track/click?u=3D13eb080d8a315477042e0d5b1&id=3De915c=
376dd&e=3Da5eb5cdf67" style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-si=
ze-adjust: 100%;color: #C33737;text-decoration: underline;">=E2=80=9Cthe h=
umane art=2C=E2=80=9D</a> the project radiates a lovely countercultural ch=
arm. Ours is the golden age of Big Data=2C where human lives are aggregate=
d into massive data sets in the hope that analysis of the aggregate would=
 yield valid insight into the individual =E2=80=94  an approach no more ef=
fective than taking an exquisite poem in English=2C running it through Goo=
gle Translate to render into Japanese=2C and then Google-translating it ba=
ck into English; the result may have the vague contours of the original po=
em=E2=80=99s meaning=2C but none of its subtle magic and vibrant granular=
 beauty.</p><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjus=
t: 100%;color: #808080;font-family: Arial=2C Sans-serif;font-size: 14px;li=
ne-height: 170%;text-align: left;">Lupi and Posavec reclaim that poetic gr=
anularity of the individual from the homogenizing aggregate-grip of Big Da=
ta. What emerges is a case for the beauty of small data and its deliberate=
 interpretation=2C analog visualization=2C and slow transmission =E2=80=94=
 a celebration of the infinitesimal=2C incomplete=2C imperfect=2C yet marv=
elously human details through which we wrest meaning out of the incomprehe=
nsible vastness of all possible experience that is life.</p></blockquote><=
